ests, comparisons |\\ndocs/milestones.md:107:# Detailed milestone plan\\ndocs/milestones.md:123:**In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.**\\ndocs/milestones.md:133:* a shared downstream readout so comparison to baselines stays fair\\ndocs/milestones.md:140:* a decoder or readout unavailable to the baselines  \\ndocs/milestones.md:145:* **`P0`**: canonical point baseline using passive leaky linear non-spiking single-compartment neurons matched to the same circuit and readout  \\ndocs/milestones.md:146:* **`P1`**: stronger reduced baseline using an effective-point or reduced-compartment model with explicit synaptic integration current or explicit delay structure\\ndocs/milestones.md:151: In a connectome-constrained Drosophila visual motion circuit, adding a morphology-resolved surface state should produce small but reproducible, geometry-dependent departures in shared circuit observables relative to fair point/reduced-neuron baselines.\\ndocs/milestones.md:153:**What should the wave model do differently than a baseline point-neuron model?**  \\ndocs/milestones.md:157: A geometry-sensitive shared-output effect, preferably on null-direction suppression or response latency, that survives a stronger reduced baseline.\\ndocs/milestones.md:174:* **Very strong:** the effect survives the stronger reduced baseline `P1`\\ndocs/milestones.md:179:2. **`10–25 s`**: split screen with matched point baseline on the left and surface model on the right for the same T4/T5-centered circuit  \\ndocs/milestones.md:187:* split view showing baseline scalar activity versus surface-state activity on morphology  \\ndocs/milestones.md:192:* `P0` versus `P1` challenge-baseline comparison plot  \\ndocs/milestones.md:208:* creating the experiment manifest schema  \\ndocs/milestones.md:229:* `P0` and `P1` baseline definitions are explicit  \\ndocs/milestones.md:242:3. survival against a stronger reduced baseline  \\ndocs/milestones.md:258:Choose and freeze the smallest scientifically defensible circuit boundary for the first real simulation pass.\\ndocs/milestones.md:290:Keep these as context-only, not active simulation:\\ndocs/milestones.md:298:Do **not** include the following in the active simulation boundary:\\ndocs/milestones.md:314:The first test stimuli should stay simple and local, using bright and dark moving edges or apparent-motion bar pairs along the chosen horizontal axis.\\ndocs/milestones.md:329:* root ID manifests for active, candidate, and context graphs  \\ndocs/milestones.md:341:* there is a named manifest for the locked boundary  \\ndocs/milestones.md:344:* the Milestone 2 boundary is frozen as the default first simulation pass  \\ndocs/milestones.md:381:- manifest validation  \\ndocs/milestones.md:392:- the same experiment can be reproduced from a manifest\\ndocs/milestones.md:424:- exporting manifests and reports\\ndocs/milestones.md:435:- each subset produces a manifest and stats file  \\ndocs/milestones.md:444:Fetch, store, simplify, and standardize neuron geometry for simulation.\\ndocs/milestones.md:489:Turn neuron surfaces into simulation-ready numerical objects.\\ndocs/milestones.md:584:- looming stimuli  \\ndocs/milestones.md:599:- defining which stimuli are best for isolating wave effects\\ndocs/milestones.md:603:- standard stimuli are callable from config  \\ndocs/milestones.md:604:- stimuli can be recorded and replayed\\ndocs/milestones.md:616:Map world-space visual stimuli into the fly’s retinotopic input representation.\\ndocs/milestones.md:630:- determining how stimuli map into early visual units\\ndocs/milestones.md:646:Create real visual environments instead of only lab stimuli.\\ndocs/milestones.md:678:## Milestone 9 — Build the baseline non-wave simulator\\ndocs/milestones.md:691:- `baseline`  \\ndocs/milestones.